1
00:00:02,001 --> 00:00:07,093
I remember when I was a child
living in Southern Maryland,

2
00:00:07,093 --> 00:00:12,694
we used to go out in the woods
searching for blackberries.

3
00:00:12,694 --> 00:00:14,607
Searching for sweetness!

4
00:00:14,997 --> 00:00:18,254
[Everyone is Searching for Sweetness]

5
00:00:18,534 --> 00:00:22,024
So, if you pulled back
the branches of the bushes,

6
00:00:22,024 --> 00:00:25,942
sometimes we’d see a turtle.

7
00:00:25,942 --> 00:00:37,359
They’d turn their heads,
their faces covered in blackberries,

8
00:00:38,394 --> 00:00:41,343
and they’d look a little surprised.

9
00:00:41,343 --> 00:00:44,645
English turtles. “Hello there.”

10
00:00:45,952 --> 00:00:47,882
But then you could see, “Oh!

11
00:00:47,882 --> 00:00:51,231
We’re searching for sweetness,

12
00:00:51,231 --> 00:00:53,271
the turtle is searching for sweetness.”

13
00:00:53,271 --> 00:00:55,129
I didn’t think like that at the time,

14
00:00:55,129 --> 00:00:59,109
but I did think it was interesting.

15
00:00:59,109 --> 00:01:06,362
I mean, on some subtle,
primitive, tribal level

16
00:01:07,105 --> 00:01:12,167
I understood,
we’re looking for the same thing.

17
00:01:12,167 --> 00:01:14,927
[Laughing]

18
00:01:17,424 --> 00:01:19,982
But I had to bend down to get them,

19
00:01:19,982 --> 00:01:22,509
he had to look up.

20
00:01:23,690 --> 00:01:25,359
So Guru Mahārāj will say,

21
00:01:25,359 --> 00:01:29,016
“Everyone is searching for sweetness.”

22
00:01:29,268 --> 00:01:33,092
The ants are searching,
the turtles are searching for sweetness,

23
00:01:33,092 --> 00:01:35,547
we’re also searching for sweetness.

